WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.800 --> 00:00:04.503
I think everything
I just played is MIDI data.

00:00:04.504 --> 00:00:08.638
And so I wrote and recorded the chorus
in my own voice,

00:00:08.639 --> 00:00:12.700
probably a couple of keys lower
than where we landed for Billie

00:00:12.701 --> 00:00:15.409
because I have a lower voice,
and just had it as this hook.

00:00:15.410 --> 00:00:16.970
I had no idea what to do with it.

00:00:16.971 --> 00:00:20.805
I sang through Auto-Tune so it
sounded very atypical of the other music

00:00:20.806 --> 00:00:21.840
that I put out.

00:00:21.841 --> 00:00:26.019
But I felt the chorus was super,
super catchy and I sat on it.

00:00:26.020 --> 00:00:27.910
I didn't have verse ideas or anything.

00:00:27.911 --> 00:00:31.542
So I had this,
"I'm not your friend" thing.

00:00:31.543 --> 00:00:35.663
And then when Billie came over at some
point later to work on something else,

00:00:35.664 --> 00:00:39.943
I pulled up this session
and played her this chorus that I had

00:00:39.944 --> 00:00:42.153
and she thought
it was infectious and cool.

00:00:42.154 --> 00:00:46.152
And the original line that I'd written
was, "You think you need a man,

00:00:46.153 --> 00:00:48.578
I think therefore I am."
And Billie was like,

00:00:48.579 --> 00:00:50.724
"Oh, it should be,
'You think that you're a man,

00:00:50.725 --> 00:00:52.746
I think therefore I am,'"
which is way cooler

00:00:52.747 --> 00:00:56.503
and actually the internal rhyme
structure of that is 'you're' and 'for',

00:00:56.504 --> 00:00:58.333
which is way better anyway.

00:00:58.334 --> 00:01:04.166
And so we threw her on the hook and then
we set about writing the verses together.

00:01:04.167 --> 00:01:07.957
When we first started this
I was in a different studio location

00:01:07.958 --> 00:01:10.508
at a house that I lived in
in Highland Park for a while

00:01:10.509 --> 00:01:14.516
and Billie was singing into
a Neumann TLM 103,

00:01:14.517 --> 00:01:16.767
which she was holding
in her hand.

00:01:16.768 --> 00:01:19.482
And so this verse vocal...

00:01:25.084 --> 00:01:30.447
So all of that stuff
is recorded on a TLM 103.

00:01:33.941 --> 00:01:36.775
And she really liked the laugh
that she did on that take.

00:01:36.776 --> 00:01:42.636
And so it was a naturally quiet laugh,
so we gained the laugh by 27 dB

00:01:42.637 --> 00:01:44.719
just so that it would pop out
in the mix.

00:01:58.136 --> 00:02:02.454
That was back in probably December,
we wrote those couple of lines.

00:02:02.455 --> 00:02:04.873
This song... oftentimes
when we're making a song

00:02:04.874 --> 00:02:07.554
it's a very short
start-to-finish process.

00:02:07.555 --> 00:02:11.355
We write everything in a day or two,
we record it over the next week or two.

00:02:11.356 --> 00:02:15.625
This song was like, each time we went
to write, we were recording while we went,

00:02:15.626 --> 00:02:20.450
but it was several days over the course
of seven or eight months

00:02:20.451 --> 00:02:22.984
to get each individual part.

00:02:22.985 --> 00:02:26.121
So literally that day,
all that we got was...

00:02:34.566 --> 00:02:35.546
That was it.

00:02:35.547 --> 00:02:38.957
And then the next time
we went to revisit it we wrote this...

00:02:48.495 --> 00:02:53.685
To me, the heart of Billie's sonics when
I'm working on it in a song like this,

00:02:53.686 --> 00:02:59.154
not in every song,
but she's such an incredible harmonizer.

00:03:04.853 --> 00:03:08.119
So there's so much chordal information
in a song that otherwise,

00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:14.239
really is a baseline and high notes
played in a syncopated pattern.

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:18.430
Most of the chord data
is actually just in her voice.

00:03:18.431 --> 00:03:22.351
And then I think the same day we did that,
we ended up writing this part

00:03:22.352 --> 00:03:24.128
which was really fun.

00:03:34.397 --> 00:03:39.737
And that was... We had the instrumental
layout of that, to be honest.

00:03:39.738 --> 00:03:44.776
We knew that we wanted the verse
to end with this stop moment,

00:03:45.101 --> 00:03:47.571
where the synths would drop out.

00:03:48.704 --> 00:03:54.116
So we had that set up to write over.

00:03:54.117 --> 00:03:58.316
And that was, as far as we got that day,
just reintroduce the chorus.

00:03:58.317 --> 00:04:04.067
We added a little dropout because the
chorus is... each chorus is a double, right?

00:04:04.068 --> 00:04:05.598
It's the entire...

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:25.989
It's really a repeat.

00:04:25.990 --> 00:04:28.700
It's like, what can we reintroduce
the second time?

00:04:28.701 --> 00:04:33.113
So, the only thing that comes in
on the second chorus, on the second half

00:04:33.114 --> 00:04:38.704
is this clap which was a thing
that Billie was doing in the room.

00:04:47.283 --> 00:04:51.381
And I thought that gave it
a really fun, lilting thing,

00:04:51.382 --> 00:04:53.103
which was really appealing to me.

00:04:53.104 --> 00:04:55.253
So I threw it in the recording.

00:04:55.254 --> 00:04:59.012
There's also this,
I'm calling it, like, cowbell-type.

00:04:59.013 --> 00:05:00.554
It's not a cowbell sample.

00:05:00.555 --> 00:05:08.816
It's actually... it's not that complicated
but it's... just that little clackety thing

00:05:08.817 --> 00:05:12.320
that rhythmically is doing
what a cowbell would do

00:05:12.321 --> 00:05:14.386
in accordance to
the kick drum maybe.

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:24.566
Which I thought gave it
a little bit more neck.

00:05:24.567 --> 00:05:29.733
And then we added this bass sweep
instead of the one in the drums

00:05:29.734 --> 00:05:31.932
on that part of the chorus,
which goes...

00:05:33.073 --> 00:05:35.489
instead of playing
the one on everything.

00:05:39.455 --> 00:05:40.964
And it's pretty understated.

00:05:40.965 --> 00:05:43.705
There's not a lot made of it,
which I thought was fun.

00:05:43.706 --> 00:05:47.455
Because we wrote the song
over the course of so many different days,

00:05:47.456 --> 00:05:50.474
each time we have to
reinspire ourselves.

00:05:50.475 --> 00:05:52.618
So we got to the second verse
and we thought,

00:05:52.619 --> 00:05:58.034
"Well, we really don't need to do
all of the rhythms of the first verse,

00:05:58.035 --> 00:06:00.975
we don't need to do the melodies
of the first verse vocally."

00:06:00.976 --> 00:06:07.951
And so in trying to reinspire us,
I reintroduced different components.

00:06:07.952 --> 00:06:11.317
So I added this
Synth Bass, a Trilian patch.

00:06:21.773 --> 00:06:29.052
And just that alone, which is very sparse
for Billie and for me to write with her

00:06:29.053 --> 00:06:32.298
completely turned the rhythmic components
of the song on their head

00:06:32.299 --> 00:06:35.322
and allowed us to go to a completely
different place rhythmically,

00:06:35.323 --> 00:06:39.904
vocally, which is this...
I don't know what to call it

00:06:39.905 --> 00:06:43.324
other than a totally
different groove, vocally.

00:06:52.802 --> 00:06:56.293
We never would've come
to that place, vocally,

00:06:56.294 --> 00:06:58.092
if we hadn't had
that rhythm change.

00:06:58.093 --> 00:07:03.395
And I think that's a lesson I'm learning
more and more in producing songs is

00:07:03.396 --> 00:07:06.284
what you're capable
of writing over what.

00:07:06.285 --> 00:07:10.664
When I first started I was exclusively
a songwriter and then a producer,

00:07:10.665 --> 00:07:13.285
where I would sit at a piano
and write a song.

00:07:13.286 --> 00:07:18.684
And then I would migrate to a DAW
and record the vocals and record the piano

00:07:18.685 --> 00:07:20.615
and maybe add some drums or some bass.

00:07:20.616 --> 00:07:24.144
As time goes on, there are totally songs
that we write that way.

00:07:24.145 --> 00:07:26.886
Billie has a song called "My Future"
that we wrote that way,

00:07:26.887 --> 00:07:29.632
where we sat at an instrument
and played the chords

00:07:29.633 --> 00:07:32.205
and then ended up ingesting it
into the system.

00:07:45.047 --> 00:07:49.177
In a case like this,
there are things about the songwriting

00:07:49.178 --> 00:07:53.616
that would never have been true
if we had tried to write it

00:07:53.617 --> 00:07:54.997
on an acoustic guitar first.

00:07:54.998 --> 00:07:59.656
So it was super advantageous to
start with the rhythmic components of it.

